      "source": "arxiv",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.11552",
      "title": "HiChunk: Evaluating and Enhancing Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Hierarchical Chunking",
      "abstract": "Abstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) enhances the response capabilities of language models by integrating external knowledge sources. However, document chunking as an important part of RAG system often lacks effective evaluation tools. This paper first analyzes why existing RAG evaluation benchmarks are inadequate for assessing document chunking quality, specifically due to evidence sparsity. Based on this conclusion, we propose HiCBench, which includes manually annotated multi-level document chunking points, synthesized evidence-dense quetion answer(QA) pairs, and their corresponding evidence sources. Additionally, we introduce the HiChunk framework, a multi-level document structuring framework based on fine-tuned LLMs, combined with the Auto-Merge retrieval algorithm to improve retrieval quality. Experiments demonstrate that HiCBench effectively evaluates the impact of differe",
      "text_preview": "HiChunk: Evaluating and Enhancing Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Hierarchical Chunking\nAbstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) enhances the response capabilities of language models by integrating external knowledge sources. However, document chunking as an important part of RAG system often lacks effective evaluation tools. This paper first analyzes why existing RAG evaluation benchmarks are inadequate for assessing document chunking quality, specifically due to evidence sparsity. Based on this conclusion, we propose HiCBench, which includes manually annotated multi-level document chunking points, synthesized evidence-dense quetion answer(QA) pairs, and their corresponding evidence sources. Additionally, we introduce the HiChunk framework, a multi-level document structuring framework based on fine-tuned LLMs, combined with the Auto-Merge retrieval algorithm to improve retrieval quality. Experiments demonstrate that HiCBench effectively evaluates the impact of differe\nAuthors:Wensheng Lu, Keyu Chen, Ruizhi Qiao, Xing Sun\n\n \n \n Computer Science > Computation and Language\n \n\n \n arXiv:2509.11552 (cs)\n \n\n \n \n [Submitted on 15 Sep 2025 (v1), last revised 9 Oct 2025 (this version, v3)]\n Title:HiChunk: Evaluating and Enhancing Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Hierarchical Chunking\n Authors:Wensheng Lu, Keyu Chen, Ruizhi Qiao, Xing Sun View a PDF of the paper titled HiChunk: Evaluating and Enhancing Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Hierarchical Chunking, by Wensheng Lu and 3 other authors\n View PDF\n HTML (experimental)\n\n \n Abstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) enhances the response capabilities of language models by integrating external knowledge sources. However, document chunking as an important part of RAG system often lacks effective evaluation tools. This paper first analyzes why existing RAG evaluation benchmarks are inadequate for assessing document chunking quality, specifically due to evidence sparsity. Based on this conclusion, we propose HiCBench, which includes manually annotated multi-level document chunking points, synthesized evidence-dense quetion answer(QA) pairs, and their corresponding evidence sources. Additionally, we introdu",
