    {
      "paper_id": "a9ec4d67-b43a-4571-bc59-5583d5ece9fb",
      "alias_paper_ids": [
        "a9ec4d67-b43a-4571-bc59-5583d5ece9fb"
      ],
      "canonical_id": "arxiv:2511.04502",
      "canonical_url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.04502",
      "source": "arxiv",
      "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.04502",
      "title": "RAGalyst: Automated Human-Aligned Agentic Evaluation for Domain-Specific RAG",
      "abstract": "Abstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a critical technique for grounding Large Language Models (LLMs) in factual evidence, yet evaluating RAG systems in specialized, safety-critical domains remains a significant challenge. Existing evaluation frameworks often rely on heuristic-based metrics that fail to capture domain-specific nuances and other works utilize LLM-as-a-Judge approaches that lack validated alignment with human judgment. This paper introduces RAGalyst, an automated, human-aligned agentic framework designed for the rigorous evaluation of domain-specific RAG systems. RAGalyst features an agentic pipeline that generates high-quality, synthetic question-answering (QA) datasets from source documents, incorporating an agentic filtering step to ensure data fidelity. The framework refines two key LLM-as-a-Judge metrics-Answer Correctness and Answerability-using prompt opt",
      "text_preview": "RAGalyst: Automated Human-Aligned Agentic Evaluation for Domain-Specific RAG\nAbstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a critical technique for grounding Large Language Models (LLMs) in factual evidence, yet evaluating RAG systems in specialized, safety-critical domains remains a significant challenge. Existing evaluation frameworks often rely on heuristic-based metrics that fail to capture domain-specific nuances and other works utilize LLM-as-a-Judge approaches that lack validated alignment with human judgment. This paper introduces RAGalyst, an automated, human-aligned agentic framework designed for the rigorous evaluation of domain-specific RAG systems. RAGalyst features an agentic pipeline that generates high-quality, synthetic question-answering (QA) datasets from source documents, incorporating an agentic filtering step to ensure data fidelity. The framework refines two key LLM-as-a-Judge metrics-Answer Correctness and Answerability-using prompt opt\nAuthors:Joshua Gao, Quoc Huy Pham, Subin Varghese, Silwal Saurav, Vedhus Hoskere\n\n \n \n Computer Science > Computation and Language\n \n\n \n arXiv:2511.04502 (cs)\n \n\n \n \n [Submitted on 6 Nov 2025]\n Title:RAGalyst: Automated Human-Aligned Agentic Evaluation for Domain-Specific RAG\n Authors:Joshua Gao, Quoc Huy Pham, Subin Varghese, Silwal Saurav, Vedhus Hoskere View a PDF of the paper titled RAGalyst: Automated Human-Aligned Agentic Evaluation for Domain-Specific RAG, by Joshua Gao and 4 other authors\n View PDF\n HTML (experimental)\n\n \n Abstract:Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a critical technique for grounding Large Language Models (LLMs) in factual evidence, yet evaluating RAG systems in specialized, safety-critical domains remains a significant challenge. Existing evaluation frameworks often rely on heuristic-based metrics that fail to capture domain-specific nuances and other works utilize LLM-as-a-Judge approaches that lack validated alignment with human judgment. This paper introduces RAGalyst, an automated, human-aligned agentic framework designed for the rigorous evaluation of domain-specific RAG systems. RAGalyst features an agentic pipeline that generates high-quality, synthetic question-ans",
